Person,&rdquo; in <em>Humanizing Modern Medicine: An Introductory
Philosophy of Medicine</em>, New York: Springer, pp. 49&ndash;61.</li>

<li> Mason, Rebecca, 2011, &ldquo;Two Kinds of Unknowing,&rdquo;
<em>Hypatia</em>, 26(2): 294&ndash;307.</li>

<li> McClain, Elizabeth K., 2017, &ldquo;Changes in Osteopathic
Medical Education: The Journey Continues,&rdquo; <em>The Journal of
the American Osteopathic Association</em>, 117(4): 208&ndash;210.</li>

<li> McClimans, Leah, 2015, &ldquo;Place of Birth: Ethics and
Evidence,&rdquo; <em>Topoi</em>, 1&ndash;8.</li>

<li> &ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2024, <em>Patient-Centered Measurement:
Ethics, Epistemology, and Dialogue in Contemporary Medicine</em>,
Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li> McKeown, Thomas, 1976, <em>The Role of Medicine: Dream, Mirage,
or Nemesis</em>, London: Nuffield Provincial Hospitals Trust.</li>

<li> Medina, Jos&eacute;, 2017, &ldquo;Varieties of Hermeneutical
Injustice,&rdquo; in Ian James Kidd, Jos&eacute; Medina, and Gaile
Pohlhaus Jr. (eds.), <em>The Routledge Handbook of Epistemic
Injustice</em>, London: Routledge, pp. 41&ndash;52.</li>

<li> Metzl, Jonathan M., and Anna Kirkland (eds.), 2010, <em>Against
Health: How Health Became the New Morality</em>, New York: New York
University Press.</li>

<li> Midanik, Lorraine T., 2004, &ldquo;Biomedicalization and Alcohol
Studies: Implications for Policy,&rdquo; <em>Journal of Public Health
Policy</em>, 25: 211&ndash;228.</li>

<li> Millum, Joseph, and Ezekiel J. Emanuel (eds.), 2012, <em>Global
Justice and Bioethics</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li> Muller, Se&aacute;n M., 2021, &ldquo;Masks, Mechanisms and
Covid-19: The Limitations of Randomized Trials in Pandemic
Policymaking,&rdquo; <em>History and Philosophy of the Life
Sciences</em>, 43(2): 43.</li>

<li> Nunn, Amy, 2009, <em>The Politics and History of AIDS Treatment
in Brazil</em>, New York: Springer Science+Business Media.</li>

<li> Owens, John, and Alan Cribb, 2019, &ldquo;&lsquo;My Fitbit Thinks
I Can Do Better!&rsquo; Do Health-Promoting Wearable Technologies
Support Personal Autonomy?&rdquo; <em>Philosophy &amp;
Technology</em>, 32(1): 23&ndash;38.</li>

<li> Parsons, Annie, and Claire Hooker, 2010, &ldquo;Dignity and
Narrative Medicine,&rdquo; <em>Journal of Bioethical Inquiry</em>,
7(4): 345&ndash;351.</li>

<li> Pe&ntilde;a-Guzm&aacute;n, David M., and Joel Michael Reynolds,
2019, &ldquo;The Harm of Ableism: Medical Error and Epistemic
Injustice,&rdquo; <em>Kennedy Institute of Ethics Journal</em>, 29(3):
205&ndash;242.</li>

<li> Pinto, Andrew D., and Ross E. G. Upshur, 2009, &ldquo;Global
Health Ethics for Students,&rdquo; <em>Developing World
Bioethics</em>, 9(1): 1&ndash;10.</li>

<li> Prainsack, Barbara, 2017, <em>Personalized Medicine: Empowered
Patients in the 21st Century?</em>, New York: NYU Press.</li>

<li> Rastogi, Sanjeev, 2014, &ldquo;Ayurvedic Principles of Food and
Nutrition: Translating Theory into Evidence-Based Practice,&rdquo; in
Sanjeev Rastogi (ed.), <em>Ayurvedic Science of Food and
Nutrition</em>, New York: Springer, pp. 3&ndash;14.</li>

<li> Ritunnano, Rosa, 2022, &ldquo;Overcoming Hermeneutical Injustice
in Mental Health: A Role for Critical Phenomenology,&rdquo;
<em>Journal of the British Society for Phenomenology</em>, 53(3):
243&ndash;260.</li>

<li> Robinson, G. Canby, 1939, <em>The Patient as a Person: A Study of
the Social Aspects of Illness</em>, New York: Commonwealth Fund.</li>

<li> Rose, Nikolas, 2007, &ldquo;Beyond Medicalisation,&rdquo; <em>The
Lancet</em>, 369(9562): 700&ndash;702.
doi:10.1016/S0140-6736(07)60319-5.</li>

<li> Rosenberg, Alex, 2006, <em>Darwinian Reductionism: Or, How to
Stop Worrying and Love Molecular Biology</em>, Chicago: University of
Chicago Press.</li>

<li> Sadler, John Z., Fabrice Jotterand, Simon Craddock Lee, and
Stephen Inrig, 2009, &ldquo;Can Medicalization Be Good? Situating
Medicalization Within Bioethics,&rdquo; <em>Theoretical Medicine and
Bioethics</em>, 30(6): 411&ndash;425.
doi:10.1007/s11017-009-9122-4.</li>

<li> Sidel, Victor W., and Ruth Sidel, 1981, &ldquo;All Self-Care Is
Not Solipsistic, but Selective Citation Surely Is: A Reply to Katz and
Levin,&rdquo; <em>International Journal of Health Services</em>,
11(4): 653&ndash;657.</li>

<li> Solomon, Miriam, 2011, &ldquo;Just a Paradigm: Evidence-Based
Medicine in Epistemological Context,&rdquo; <em>European Journal for
Philosophy of Science</em>, 1(3): 451&ndash;466.</li>

<li> &ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2015, <em>Making Medical Knowledge</em>,
New York: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li> &ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2021, &ldquo;On the Concept of
&lsquo;Psychiatric Disorder&rsquo;: Incorporating Psychological
Injury,&rdquo; <em>Philosophy, Psychiatry, &amp; Psychology</em>,
28(4): 329&ndash;339.</li>

<li> Spencer, Lucienne J., 2023, &ldquo;Hermeneutical Injustice and
Unworlding in Psychopathology,&rdquo; <em>Philosophical
Psychology</em>, 1&ndash;26.</li>

<li> Spencer, Lucienne J., and Havi Carel, 2021,
&ldquo;&lsquo;Isn&rsquo;t Everyone a Little OCD?&rsquo; The Epistemic
Harms of Wrongful Depathologization,&rdquo; <em>Philosophy of
Medicine</em>, 2(1): 1&ndash;18.</li>

<li> Spencer, Lucienne J., and Ian James Kidd, 2023, &ldquo;&lsquo;The
Hermeneutic Problem of Psychiatry&rsquo; and the Co-Production of
Meaning in Psychiatric Healthcare,&rdquo; <em>Royal Institute of
Philosophy Supplements</em>, 94: 103&ndash;131.</li>

<li> Stark, John E., 2013, &ldquo;An Historical Perspective on
Principles of Osteopathy,&rdquo; <em>International Journal of
Osteopathic Medicine</em>, 16(1): 3&ndash;10.</li>

<li> Stegenga, Jacob, 2011, &ldquo;Is Meta-Analysis the Platinum
Standard of Evidence?&rdquo; <em>Studies in History and Philosophy of
Biological and Biomedical Sciences</em>, 42(4): 497&ndash;507.</li>

<li> &ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2018, <em>Medical Nihilism</em>, Oxford:
Oxford University Press.</li>

<li> Svenaeus, Fredrik, 2019, &ldquo;A Defense of the Phenomenological
Account of Health and Illness,&rdquo; <em>The Journal of Medicine and
Philosophy: A Forum for Bioethics and Philosophy of Medicine</em>,
44(4): 459&ndash;478.</li>

<li> &ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2023, &ldquo;The Phenomenology of
Objectification in and Through Medical Practice and Technology
Development,&rdquo; <em>The Journal of Medicine and Philosophy</em>,
48(2): 141&ndash;150.</li>

<li> Szasz, Thomas, 1960, &ldquo;The Myth of Mental Illness,&rdquo;
<em>American Psychologist</em>, 15(2): 113&ndash;118.
doi:10.1037/h0046535.</li>

<li> &ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2007, <em>The Medicalization of Everyday
Life: Selected Essays</em>, Syracuse: Syracuse University Press.</li>

<li> Tabery, James, 2023, <em>Tyranny of the Gene: Personalized
Medicine and Its Threat to Public Health</em>, New York: Knopf.</li>

<li> Tal, Eran, 2025, &ldquo;Models and Measurement,&rdquo; in Tarja
Knuuttila, Natalia Carrillo, and Rami Koskinen (eds.), <em>The
Routledge Handbook of Philosophy of Scientific Modeling</em>, London:
Routledge, pp. 256&ndash;269.</li>

<li> Tonelli, Mark R., and Timothy C. Callahan, 2001, &ldquo;Why
Alternative Medicine Cannot Be Evidence-Based,&rdquo; <em>Academic
Medicine</em>, 76(12): 1213&ndash;1220.</li>

<li> Tonelli, Mark R., and Ross E. G. Upshur, 2019, &ldquo;A
Philosophical Approach to Addressing Uncertainty in Medical
Education,&rdquo; <em>Academic Medicine</em>, 94(4): 507&ndash;511.
doi:10.1097/ACM.0000000000002512.</li>

<li> Valles, Sean A., 2018, <em>Philosophy of Population Health:
Philosophy for a New Public Health Era</em>, Abingdon, Oxon:
Routledge.</li>

<li> Vogt, Henrik, Bj&oslash;rn Hofmann, and Linn Getz, 2016,
&ldquo;The New Holism: P4 Systems Medicine and the Medicalization of
Health and Life Itself,&rdquo; <em>Medicine, Health Care and
Philosophy</em>, 19(2): 307&ndash;323.
doi:10.1007/s11019-016-9683-8.</li>

<li> Vogt, Henrik, Elling Ulvestad, Thor Eirik Eriksen, and Linn Getz,
2014, &ldquo;Getting Personal: Can Systems Medicine Integrate
Scientific and Humanistic Conceptions of the Patient?&rdquo;
<em>Journal of Evaluation in Clinical Practice</em>, 20(6):
942&ndash;9952. doi:10.1111/jep.12251.</li>

<li> Wanderer, Jeremy, 2017, &ldquo;Varieties of Testimonial
Injustice,&rdquo; in Ian James Kidd, Jos&eacute; Medina, and Gaile
Pohlhaus Jr. (eds.), <em>The Routledge Handbook of Epistemic
Injustice</em>, London: Routledge, pp. 27&ndash;40.</li>

<li> Wardrope, Alistair, 2015, &ldquo;Medicalization and Epistemic
Injustice,&rdquo; <em>Medicine, Health Care and Philosophy</em>,
18(3): 341&ndash;352. doi:10.1007/s11019-014-9608-3.</li>

<li> Wieten, Sarah, 2018, &ldquo;Expertise in Evidence-Based Medicine:
A Tale of Three Models,&rdquo; <em>Philosophy, Ethics, and Humanities
in Medicine</em>, 13(1): 2. doi:10.1186/s13010-018-0053-7.</li>

<li> Wolfe, Charles T., 2015, &ldquo;Was Canguilhem a Biochauvinist?
Goldstein, Canguilhem and the Project of Biophilosophy,&rdquo; in
Darian Meacham (ed.), <em>Medicine and Society: New Perspectives in
Continental Philosophy</em>, Dordrecht: Springer, pp.
197&ndash;212.</li>

<li> Woods, Angela, 2011, &ldquo;The Limits of Narrative: Provocations
for the Medical Humanities,&rdquo; <em>Medical Humanities</em>, 37(2):
73&ndash;78.</li>

<li> Woods, Simon, 2017, &ldquo;Holism in Health Care: Patient as
Person,&rdquo; in Thomas Schramme and Steven Edwards (eds.),
<em>Handbook of the Philosophy of Medicine</em>, Dordrecht:
Springer.</li>

<li> Worrall, John, 2007, &ldquo;Why There&rsquo;s No Cause to
Randomize,&rdquo; <em>The British Journal for the Philosophy of
Science</em>, 58(3): 451&ndash;488. doi:10.1093/bjps/axm024.</li>

<li> Y&uuml;ksekda&#287;, Yusuf, 2020, &ldquo;Individual
Responsibilities in Partial Compliance: Skilled Health Worker
Emigration from Under-Served Regions,&rdquo; <em>Public Health
Ethics</em>, 13(1): 89&ndash;98. doi:10.1093/phe/phz016.</li>

<li> Zola, Irving Kenneth, 1976, &ldquo;Medicine as an Institution of
Social Control,&rdquo; <em>Ekistics</em>, 41(245):
210&ndash;214.x</li>
</ul>
</div> 

